column1: #Probe Set ID:          The probeset ID used in the final product. For now we are still using DMET3B IDs
column2: but will move to opaque IDs from the sequence of IDs for product launch.

column1: #Associated Gene:       The gene symbol that was designated for this marker in the input files. If the marker is a cluster of >1 input lines
column2: then the gene symbol from the highest priority input is used.

column1: #dbSNP RS ID:           dbSNP ids that map to the same location. The dbSNP alleles need not be the same as the ADME alleles. The 2 allele sets are merged at this location.

column2: parsed from various underlying data sources and then manually curated.

column1: #Chromosome:            Chromosome upon which the marker is located
#Physical Position:     The single base (as opposed to interbase) at which the mutation maps. Multibase alleles are mapped to the first base location
column2: on the plus strand (following the dbSNP system).More stringent mapping data is found in the .info file.

column1: #Genome Context:        The alleles and flanking sequences on the PLUS strand
column2: with nearby variations shown in angle brackets (merged from genome

column1: #Design Strand:         The strand of genome (ncbi 36) upon which the MIP probes were designed and which was used as the forward strand of the array design.
#Alleles Design Strand: The alleles found on the Design Strand
#Allele Code:           The codes used for the alleles in the CDF and CHP files
column2: in the same order as Alleles Design Strand are presented

column1: #Gene Strand:           the strand of the genome (ncbi36) which is the coding strand of Associated Gene
#Switch Design Strand to Report:  If the Design Strand and the Gene Strand are different
column2: then switch=1. This means that we need to report the alleles on the opposite strand to the design strand
column3: so that we are now reporting on the same strand as the Associated gene.

column2: in the same order as Alleles Design Strand and Allele Code
column3: on the reported strand (which will be the same as Alleles Design Strand if switch=0).

column2: the strand of the genome (ncbi 36) that we are reporting.

column1: #DbSNP annot:           Some annotation from the dbSNP entry
#PharmGKB Code:         The ID associated with this Associated Gene in the PharmGKB database.
#Alleles-Alias Reported Strand: An alias to substitute in the reporting GUI
column2: for actual allele sequences that are too long or are better summarised by a trivial name.

column3: paired with the sequence data shown in the Context Sequence field.

column1: #Context Sequence:      The actual sequence for each context (after the nearby variations have been resolved). One-to-one pairing with the codes in the Context Code field.
#Reference Genome Flank: The alleles and NCBI reference genome flanking sequences.
#CN Region:		The name of the copy number region within which a marker exists
#mPCR Region:		Flag to show the marker lies within an mPCR amplicon.
